Replay attacks happen when someone secretly captures a valid message or data and then sends it again later to trick a system into accepting it twice. This can let attackers repeat actions like logging in or making transactions without permission. To stop this, systems use things like timestamps, unique codes, or one-time tokens to make sure each message is fresh and can’t be reused. Searching terms like “replay attack prevention,” “nonces,” or “message authentication” can reveal more. Understanding these helps protect private conversations and keep digital interactions secure.